Abstract
High demand for computational power significantly limits the possibility of
using modern deep learning methods in the environments where one has to deal
with devices limited by the performance and the energy constraints. To address
this issue, this paper proposes a novel method of combining the pruning and the
transfer learning (TL) techniques for the purpose of delivering solid accuracy
while simultaneously lowering the demand for energy and computing power.
This method is referred to as finicky TL as it is finicky during the process of
selecting filters from a pretrained feature extractor to compose a sparser archi-
tecture. The proposed filter selection process is based on an original approach
utilizing the Jaccard similarity coefficient calculated between the activation
maps and the masks obtained by semantic segmentation. This enables the use
of convolutional neural networks, trained previously on a large generic dataset,
in a crack classification task. The presented method significantly lowers the
inference time while maintaining or even slightly increasing the classification
accuracy, enabling real-time operation on single-board computers.

Recently, pruning has become an intense research
topic. Its main goal relies on removing redundant network
parameters while minimizing the loss of classification
accuracy. This procedure allows the reduction of computa-
tion time and memory usage. Some publications (Blalock
et al., 2020) have demonstrated the effectiveness of these
methods in relation to convolutional neural networks
(CNNs). Additionally, in some cases, pruning methods
can increase the accuracy of base models (Han et al., 2015;
Suzuki et al., 2020).
The abovementioned advancements should be con-
sidered for the application in civil infrastructure health
monitoring, as it is in dire need of DL methods. It is
particularly evident in the field of maintenance, where
labor-intensive manual methods are still used (Jeong et al.,
2018; Washer et al., 2019). These methods yield unsatisfac-
tory results, as over6 0 \%of infrastructure defects can be
omitted during such inspections (Phares et al., 2001).
In recent studies, attempts have been made to solve
these problems both with the help of a traditional com-
puter vision (Adhikari et al., 2012) and with the methods
employing DL algorithms. Although the former proved
to be highly susceptible to the lighting and surface
changes, showing inability to generalize the developed
model (Dorafshan et al., 2018), the latter, using convolu-
tional (Atha & Jahanshahi, 2018; Oh et al., 2020), fully
convolutional (Dung & Anh, 2019; Li et al., 2019), and Long
short-term memory (LSTM) (Zhang et al., 2019) networks,
achieved very good accuracy in the presented test cases.
However, these complex algorithms are difficult to use
on edge devices due to excessive computing power require-
ments. Bertino et al. (2021) clearly underlined the need to
reduce training time and the size of DNNs in the context of
the internet of things (IoT) devices for civil infrastructure
health monitoring. They also pointed to TL and pruning as
the main means to achieve this.
Therefore, we propose finicky transfer learning (FTL),
a method that combines pruning and TL. Its name under-
lines the fact that it is finicky in the sense of filter selection
while composing a feature extractor to be used in a new
task. The worst performing kernels are removed from the
base CNN model, and a new network containing much
fewer parameters is formed. The filter selection process
itself is based on an original approach utilizing the Jaccard
similarity coefficient (Jaccard, 1912) calculated between
the activation maps and the data specific to the semantic
segmentation. This enables the assessment of the useful-
ness of convolutional filters trained on a different dataset.
The main goal is to deliver a reliable method that will
allow the use of pretrained CNNs more effectively than
with traditional TL for the classification task. FTL is
efficient both in terms of reducing the inference speed and
keeping the high accuracy of model predictions. For the
method implementation, a test case of crack classification
specific to infrastructure maintenance was selected. This
problem is widely recognized, and accurate methods
for detecting this type of defects (Bang et al., 2019; Cha
et al., 2017) along with public datasets (Özgenel, 2019)
already exist.
This paper is organized as follows. In Section 2, the
selected works connected with CNNs pruning and TL are
mentioned. In Section 3, the principles of the developed
method are presented in details. Then, in Section 4,
the experiment details with tested architectures and
used hyperparameters are described. In Section 5, the
evaluation results for the crack classification problem
are presented. The analysis of the results is performed
on the basis of the network metrics, as well as savings
in model size and inference time. Additionally, in this
section, a benchmark on edge-computing single-board
computers is shown. Finally, in Section 6, the discussion
about the proposed method is provided, and in Section 7
conclusions as well as further development and other
application possibilities are presented.

ments. Bertino et al. (2021) clearly underlined the need to
reduce training time and the size of DNNs in the context of
the internet of things (IoT) devices for civil infrastructure
health monitoring. They also pointed to TL and pruning as
the main means to achieve this.
Therefore, we propose finicky transfer learning (FTL),
a method that combines pruning and TL. Its name under-
lines the fact that it is finicky in the sense of filter selection
while composing a feature extractor to be used in a new
task. The worst performing kernels are removed from the
base CNN model, and a new network containing much
fewer parameters is formed. The filter selection process
itself is based on an original approach utilizing the Jaccard
similarity coefficient (Jaccard, 1912) calculated between
the activation maps and the data specific to the semantic
segmentation. This enables the assessment of the useful-
ness of convolutional filters trained on a different dataset.
The main goal is to deliver a reliable method that will
allow the use of pretrained CNNs more effectively than
with traditional TL for the classification task. FTL is
efficient both in terms of reducing the inference speed and
keeping the high accuracy of model predictions. For the
method implementation, a test case of crack classification
specific to infrastructure maintenance was selected. This
problem is widely recognized, and accurate methods
for detecting this type of defects (Bang et al., 2019; Cha
et al., 2017) along with public datasets (Özgenel, 2019)
already exist.

TL methods are extensively described in the literature
regarding DL algorithm building and application (Gupta
et al., 2020). They consist of various approaches, such as
using a pretrained algorithm in its entirety, using it as a
feature extractor or as a base model for fine-tuning on mul-

to DL algorithms trained from scratch, these methods fea-
ture significant limitations. The first and most important
one is the problem of negative transfer, which leads to low-
ering the accuracy of the network. It is caused by reusing
the parts of the original algorithm that influence the
overall accuracy on the new dataset negatively (Williams
et al., 2020). The algorithms obtained using TL also have
the lower ability to generalize knowledge between varying
data (Ada et al., 2019). Furthermore, they offer fewer
opportunities to improve their accuracy when transferring
knowledge between datasets (Neyshabur et al., 2020).
Some of the limitations mentioned above have already
been addressed. One of the most common methods to
increase the accuracy of the TL-trained algorithms to a
limited extent is to use extensively augmented data in
the training process, especially when a narrow dataset
is available (Milicevic et al., 2018). It is also possible to
use model ensembles (Alam et al., 2020). The other two
noteworthy methods of improving the efficiency of such
algorithms have been developed independently, but share
the same name—selective TL. The first attempt at selective
TL is focused on automating the selection of training data
domain for recommendation systems in a way that will
ensure that it stays consistent with its target (Lu et al.,
2012). The second approach to this subject aims at select-
ing only the best performing models from ensembles, thus
lowering the negative transfer (Ge et al., 2017).
2.3 Pruning
Recently, some solutions connected with the pruning of
CNNs have been proposed. Singh et al. (2020) presented
a framework for pruning of CNNs that maintain the given
error tolerance. A filter importance value is calculated
by summing the absolute values of its parameters. An
application of their method on various architectures such
as MobileNet, ResNet, and VGG16 leads to time and
memory savings. Abbasi-Asl and Yu (2020) introduced
a method based on the comparison of classification
accuracy of the network with and without a given filter.
The least important filters are then iteratively removed. In
another approach (Molchanov et al., 2019), the first- and
second-order Taylor expansions are calculated on the basis
of gradients and weights of the network. Experiments
performed on different architectures and datasets (e.g.,
ImageNet or CIFAR-10) demonstrate the high effective-
ness of the method. Zhao et al. (2019) proposed a pruning
method based on a distribution of channel saliency, which
is a parameter of a slightly modified batch normalization
layer. A pruning algorithm connected with a Small-World
approach is shown by Krishnan et al. (2019). This concept
is similar to friendship networks and uses an assessment
of the contribution of a given neuron (or a feature map)
to output classes. One of the advantages is the preparation
of a pruned structure before the training of the network.
A proposition of pruning called Gate Decorator is shown
in You et al. (2019). The outputs of filters are multiplied
by a trainable factor, and the changes of loss are evaluated
using Taylor series. Then, the most important filters are
selected. Furthermore, a special procedure called Tick-
Tock is described. A method that applies different pruning
criteria for various layers is presented by He et al. (2020).
Furthermore, an overview of networks pruning
achievements is performed by Blalock et al. (2020).

with neural networks pruning. They also described the
main problems of these papers, such as ignoring pre-2010s
algorithms or performing experiments that are difficult
to understand. This assessment is caused, for instance,
using various datasets and metrics. This makes it difficult
to compare the results achieved by different authors.

3 PROPOSED METHOD
The TL methods presented in Section 2 do not solve all the
problems that affect DL algorithms mentioned in Section 1.
Still, even when employing them, vast datasets have to be
used, or model ensembles have to be trained, increasing
inference time to an even greater extent. To address these
issues, we have developed FTL—a method that combines
TL and pruning. As seen in Figure 1, this solution uses
both pretrained network and labeled data. For pruning
itself, a segmented subdataset is used, containing the sam-
ples of the new dataset with their segmented counterparts.
Based on the resulting activation maps, a decision is made
which filters can be removed. The pruned architecture is
then used as a feature extractor for a logistic regression
model. It means that during the fine-tuning phase, the
original architecture—except for the classifying layer—is
not retrained. FTL also allows reducing classifier training
time, as it operates on a smaller feature vector than the ini-
tial CNN. However, other methods for shortening training
time can also be applied (Pereira et al., 2020). The proposed
approach leads to the algorithm which alleviates the obsta-
cles of the practical use of complex classification methods.
The novelty of the proposed approach is reflected by two
aspects. The first and the most important aspect is that
the proposed method does not require the retraining of
the utilized model. This is a unique feature of the pro-
posed approach when compared with the existing meth-
ods. For example, in Liu et al. (2017), one of the initial steps
of the algorithm is the iterative pruning of the base net-
work using source data. In the recently proposed method
in Wu et al. (2019), the first parameters of the original net-
work are first fine-tuned with the crack-training dataset,
and next it is required that the whole pruned network is
again fine-tuned with the trained data. Similarly, training
of the pretrained network is required in the scheme pro-
posed in Reinhold and Roisenberg (2019). In contrast, the
algorithm proposed in this paper performs pruning using
only the target domain. This makes our method much
more computationally efficient, as it requires the retrain-
ing using the classification layers only. One should note
that, as we have designed our solution especially for cracks
classification, the main goal was the simplicity of the algo-
rithm and the elimination of the network retraining using
a complex source dataset.
The second advantage of the proposed method also
stems from the designed principles used during its devel-
opment. Recent approaches based on using pruning in
combination with TL were designed with NLP applications
in mind (Gordon et al., 2020; Guo et al., 2020). As such,
they are not suitable for using in computer vision. This is
confirmed in Guo et al. (2020) where the authors suggest
that their method could be used for computer vision
without giving any details. To the contrary, the approach
presented in this paper was developed specifically for the
purpose of processing images. Thus, the proposed method
provides a unique approach for combining the TL and
pruning, being at the same time designed specifically with
a computer vision applications in mind.

∙ data preparation—a part of the dataset is selected for the
segmentation;
∙ CNN pruning—filters are reduced on the pretrained net-
work, based on the previously prepared images;
∙ training of a logistic regression;

3.1 Data preparation
Despite being an image classification task, a specific kind
of image data has to be prepared for FTL. These data are
identical to the datasets used in semantic segmentation
and contain a homogeneous set of pixels extracted from
the image marked as areas containing or not the searched
object or its specific features. This subdataset is extracted
from the training part of the main dataset. It serves only
as a template for deciding if the specific parts of the CNN
model are extracting features from the desired region—
thus, it is excluded from the training dataset. Therefore, not
all the images in the training dataset have to be segmented
for pruning. However, they should be spread evenly, not
to include bias toward any distinguishable cases for all
classes that are to be recognized by the classifier.
At the same time, such division makes it possible to
select specific features on which the classifier should focus
independently. This will reduce the occurrence of cases in
which the background features have a decisive influence
on the classification of the image.

in Section 4, the images are resized in the same manner
as during the forward data propagation through the CNN
model. This will allow deciding whether CNN focuses

processing and also excluded from the training dataset,
now containing 720 images per class. Despite the fact
that no particular crack features are sought in the images
containing background, this class also had to be included
in the data for CNN editing. Compared to the test set,
containing 3200 images, the number of the segmented
images is just its small fraction. The whole segmentation
process took less than^ { 2 \mathrm { h } }of manual labor to complete.

The comparison results show that using FTL, it is
possible to obtain performance comparable with full-
scale CPUs using low-powered single-board computers
while maintaining high metrics of the used CNN model.
Although the most basic model of the tested single-board
computers still could not match the performance of the
high-powered CPU, even with additional cooling prevent-

to obtain satisfactory performance. Raspberry Pi 3B and 4
were able to outperform high-end CPU with CNN models
containing3 . 5 \%and9 . 1 \%of parameters, respectively. Both
these ranges feature pruned VGG networks with accuracy
reaching or exceeding full, unpruned CNN.
The conducted test confirms the applicability of the
proposed method to support DL on power-efficient edge
devices. It can help in producing efficient battery-powered
applications like in Awolusi et al. (2018) and also in high-
performance CCTV-based DL systems as in Xu (2021).

7 CONCLUSIONS AND FUTURE
WORKS
The main contribution of the presented work is a novel
method of combining TL with pruning, developed for
utilizing edge computing for infrastructure maintenance.
The proposed method—FTL—allows reducing the num-
ber of network parameters while maintaining the high
classification accuracy. Combining the idea of using a
network trained on the other dataset with the pruning of
redundant parameters and the exclusion of the retraining
phase facilitates the use of the proposed method on
computers with limited computing resources. Thus, the
presented method can be useful for battery-powered
mobile devices, for example, IoT endpoints. Shortening
the computation time allows for extending battery life,
which is crucial for the network reachability period of
the device (Huang et al., 2019). As such, the proposed
solution provides a viable approach for the development
of cost-effective methods for supporting CNN training for
real-time IoT and edge-computing applications.
Moreover, using FTL along with publicly available
methods for supporting the development of image-based
DL framework such as KrakN (Żarski et al., 2020), cost-
efficient and fast DL methods can be employed by govern-
mental public workers regardless of their level of computer
proficiency. The development of efficient CNN pruning
algorithms may lead the industry to shift toward the uti-
lization of handheld, IoT, or edge-computing devices for
efficiently managing computing resources in the future.
However, certain limitations of the presented method
have to be noted. For the case study presented in this paper,
a specific dataset containing relatively simple objects was
used. Although it proved to be easy to segment out of
the training data, other objects for detection may turn
out to be more challenging. The presented classification
problem, as well as the types of networks used, are other
factors that could affect FTL method performance. In
future works, both these problems should be addressed to
prove to a greater extent the legitimacy of the use of the
proposed method. Using FTL with more complex objects
to be identified and CNNs with various microarchitectures
should be considered.

7 CONCLUSIONS AND FUTURE
WORKS
The main contribution of the presented work is a novel
method of combining TL with pruning, developed for
utilizing edge computing for infrastructure maintenance.
The proposed method—FTL—allows reducing the num-
ber of network parameters while maintaining the high
classification accuracy. Combining the idea of using a
network trained on the other dataset with the pruning of
redundant parameters and the exclusion of the retraining
phase facilitates the use of the proposed method on
computers with limited computing resources. Thus, the
presented method can be useful for battery-powered
mobile devices, for example, IoT endpoints. Shortening
the computation time allows for extending battery life,
which is crucial for the network reachability period of
the device (Huang et al., 2019). As such, the proposed
solution provides a viable approach for the development
of cost-effective methods for supporting CNN training for
real-time IoT and edge-computing applications.
Moreover, using FTL along with publicly available
methods for supporting the development of image-based
DL framework such as KrakN (Żarski et al., 2020), cost-
efficient and fast DL methods can be employed by govern-
mental public workers regardless of their level of computer
proficiency. The development of efficient CNN pruning
algorithms may lead the industry to shift toward the uti-
lization of handheld, IoT, or edge-computing devices for
efficiently managing computing resources in the future.
However, certain limitations of the presented method
have to be noted. For the case study presented in this paper,
a specific dataset containing relatively simple objects was
used. Although it proved to be easy to segment out of
the training data, other objects for detection may turn
out to be more challenging. The presented classification
problem, as well as the types of networks used, are other
factors that could affect FTL method performance. In
future works, both these problems should be addressed to
prove to a greater extent the legitimacy of the use of the
proposed method. Using FTL with more complex objects
to be identified and CNNs with various microarchitectures
should be considered.
